@node "CanDo_Features_New" "CanDo v2.5x general user interface changes..."
@toc "CanDo_Main"
@{fg highlight}MainPanel@{fg text}
   The general look of the main panel has been cleaned up.  Everything is
still there, but almost everything has been moved around.

   The XtraTools menu and icon have been removed and replaced with a list
actually on the main panel.  Some of the object tools that used to be in
the Xtra list are now in the main object panel.

   Edit routine menu item has returned to the main object panel.  It is the
last icon on the right and has the word @{fg highlight}Routines@{fg text} on it.  Clicking on it
takes you directly to the script editor as the old menu item did.

   The window editor has been moved out of the object area and placed
beside the card editor icon.
   
@{fg highlight}Color Selector@{fg text}

   The color selectors, those tiny boxes of colors in some of the
requesters, now show the register color for the selected color.  In order
to accomplish this we had to make the arrows a little smaller.

@{fg highlight}Border Requester@{fg text}

   There is a menu item that allows you to turn on and off the Sample
window shown in the current card's screen.  If the sample window is not
opened you will have a little more memory available.  The border requester
also got the enhanced @{fg highlight}Color Selectors@{fg text}.

@{fg highlight}Font Requester@{fg text}

   We now fully support Compugraphic and Color fonts.  The font list is
now cached, so on its second time thru the font requester it comes up much
MUCH faster.  There is a menu item to force a font list rescan.

   There is a menu item that allows you to turn on and off the Sample
window shown in the current card's screen.  If the sample window is not
opened you will have a little more memory available while getting rid of
unnessary font render or rescaling.  The font requester also got the
enhanced @{fg highlight}Color Selectors@{fg text}.

@endnode

@node "CanDo_Editor_New" "CanDo v2.5x script editor changes..."
@toc "CanDo_Main"
@{fg highlight}Layout EditorTool@{fg text}

   This tool, used to be in ProPak, allows you flow text around
things in you card's window.  See @{" Layout EditorTool " link "CanDo_LayOut_Editor"} help
for details.

@{fg highlight}Script Editor@{fg text}

   The script editor has been enlarged slightly and the BigEd option has
been removed since the new size is bigger than the old BigEd option.  There
are now nine editor tools visible at any one time.  The @{fg highlight}Ok@{fg text}, @{fg highlight}Cancel@{fg text} and
@{fg highlight}Help@{fg text} buttons have been moved to the right side of the display.

   There are no other changes to the user interface of the script editor.
   
@{fg highlight}Online Help@{fg text}

   We now use AmigaGUIDE for script editor lexicon help.  A side effect of
this is that Searching and Inserting Command Templates are no longer
supported.

@{fg highlight}Command Shortcuts@{fg text}

   CanDo's Script Editor now supports command shortcuts.  This allows you
to type abbreviated text and expand it into valid CanDo text.  For this to
work, a file called "EditorShortCuts.Doc" must exist in the
CanDo:CanDoFiles directory.  The format for this file is...

   @{fg highlight}«Keyword»,replacement text@{fg text}
   ..more keywords as needed..
   
   The strange characters before and after the keyword are Alt-9 and Alt-0.
Anything following the comma after te Alt-0 is considered the replacement
text.  The keyword can be any set of characters.

   As you type into the script editor, you can press @{fg highlight}Shift-Space@{fg text} which
will look in the keyword list for the previously typed word and will replace
it with the replacement text given for the found keyword.  If the keyword
is not found, a question mark will be typed in.  The replacement text is
literally typed in, so if you want a space to be typed at the end of the
replacement text you must make sure it is at the end of the replacement
text in the "EditorShortCuts.Doc" file.

@endnode

@node "CanDo_Tools_New" "CanDo v2.5x new or changed object tools..."
@toc "CanDo_Main"
@{fg highlight}SuperMover@{fg text}

   This new tool allows you to move around groups of objects.  See
@{" SuperMover Tool " link "CanDo_SuperMover_Editor"} help for details.

@{fg highlight}Window@{fg text}

   The window object got a complete overhaul in order to support 2.x and
3.x.  For more information refer to the @{" Window Editor " link "CanDo_Window_Editor"}.

@endnode

@node "CanDo_Installation_New" "CanDo v2.5x Installation comments..."
@toc "CanDo_Main"
@{fg highlight}CanDo Installation@{fg text}

   Simply click on the InstallCanDo icon and the installer will step you
thru the installation procedure.

@{fg highlight}CanDo: Assignment@{fg text}

   CanDo v2.5x now requires assignment CanDo:.  If you install using the
provided installer program the assignment will be added to your
user-startup script.
   
@{fg highlight}Manual Installation@{fg text}

   For those "Amiga Experts" out there who insist on doing a manual
install, we have provided these instructions.  These instructions assume
you have an average level of AmigaDOS and CLI knowledge.
   
If you are installing over an existing CanDo you should delete the
following files and directories before trying to install the new version of
CanDo.

  Files...
   CanDo and CanDo.info
   
  Directories...
   CanDoFiles, HelpFiles, ObjectTools, EditorTools, Utilities and XtraTools
   
Open a new CLI and please follow all the instructions carefully.  The
@{fg highlight}Quoted@{fg text} lines should be typed in literally.

   Create an empty drawer or directory where you want CanDo to reside
   
   Assign DestDir: to that newly created drawer or directory
   
   Insert the CanDoProgram disk
   
   "@{fg highlight}Copy CanDo:CanDoStuff to DestDir:@{fg text}"
   
   "@{fg highlight}Copy CanDo:C to DestDir:C@{fg text}"
   
   "@{fg highlight}Copy CanDo:Helpfiles to DestDir:HelpFiles@{fg text}"
   
   "@{fg highlight}Copy CanDo:Libs/CanDo.library to Libs:@{fg text}"
   
   "@{fg highlight}Copy CanDo:Libs/InovaMusic.library to Libs:@{fg text}"
   
   If you are running Intuition/AmigaDOS LESS than 2.10
      "@{fg highlight}Copy CanDo:Libs/ASL.library to Libs:@{fg text}"
   
   If you are running Intuition/AmigaDOS LESS than 3.00
      "@{fg highlight}Copy CanDo:Libs/AmigaGUIDE.library to Libs:@{fg text}"
      "@{fg highlight}Copy CanDo:Utilities to Sys:Utilities@{fg text}"
      "@{fg highlight}Copy CanDo:S to S:@{fg text}"
   
   Remove the CanDoProgram disk
   
   Insert the CanDoExtras disk
   
   "@{fg highlight}Copy CanDoExtras:CanDoStuff to DestDir: All@{fg text}"
   
   Remove the CanDoExtras disk
   
   Insert the CanDoExamples disk
   
   "@{fg highlight}Copy CanDoExamples:CanDoStuff to DestDir: All@{fg text}"
   
   Remove the CanDoExamples disk
   
You will need to add a line to your S:User-Startup that assigns CanDo:  to
the directory you created in the first step.  You will possibly have to
clean up the positioning of the various icon that were installed.  It might
be best to reboot in order to flush all those old libraries.

@endnode

